# Line-ending normalization.
#
# All text files are stored with LF in the repository. Git normalizes line endings
# on commit, so the working-tree convention (e.g. CRLF on a Windows checkout) never
# leaks into a commit.
#
# Why this exists: the scheduled Azure DevOps job (.azuredevops/scheduled-run.yml)
# clones on a windows-latest agent (core.autocrlf=true => CRLF working tree) and then
# runs `git add *`. Without these rules that re-committed every unmodified source file
# with CRLF endings on each "Data Update" commit, producing whole-file line-ending
# churn and recurring merge conflicts. `text=auto` makes commits LF regardless of any
# core.autocrlf setting on the committing machine, so the churn cannot happen.
* text=auto

# Byte-sensitive golden test data — freeze exactly as committed, never EOL-convert.
*.html         -text
*.verified.txt -text
*.received.txt -text

# Match .editorconfig: Windows batch files keep CRLF, shell scripts keep LF.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
*.sh  text eol=lf

# Binary assets: never apply end-of-line conversion (future-proofing; text=auto also
# auto-detects binary content, these just make intent explicit).
*.png     binary
*.jpg     binary
*.jpeg    binary
*.gif     binary
*.ico     binary
*.pdf     binary
*.zip     binary
*.pkl     binary
*.joblib  binary
*.parquet binary
*.xlsx    binary
*.onnx    binary
